                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Corajr, it also depends how you haste your pet. I dont use my level 55 buff, but the 39 one from my SS leggings, it's more than enough and it will keep you from being raped. I was always able to channel through a hasted pet. But you dont have to. You just need to be far away from your pet, with it targeted. When charm breaks, instantly cast ST. Then recharm. And, as was posted, keep your mob rooted. Some people use root on pet after it breaks charm but I fail to see the logic in that. Why would I want to root my pet ? then i would have to wait for root to break, it's pointless. When you have a charmed pet you want to kill non-stop. You cant afford dead times.<br /><br />And why should I not pull with slow ? Aggro ? Bah :) Of course it's aggro, but who cares ? I usually find my target and pull with slow, then I run to pet, press my attack button while passing pet, then just turn and use fast casting root on the mob (Root or Immobilize). There you go, mob is slowed, mob is rooted, pet is already attacking, pet takes lot less beating. If the mob is not undead, then I just pull with Deflux.<br /><br />I have found that the best trick in charm fighting is to avoid as much as possible having targeted something else but your pet. When you go pull, when you med, when do you anthing else but casting on your mob, have your pet targeted. Every second you lose trying to target your ex-pet, is another second you get raped by a hasted mob. You want to avoid that :)<br /><br /><center><img src="http://home.t-online.de/home/iranicus/images/iranicus_lotj.jpg"><br><br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=12328" target="_new">My Gear</a><br /></center></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
